</arg></template><bold>Cluny</bold><space/>or<space/><bold>Clugny</bold><space/>is a<space/><link><target>Communes of France</target><part>commune</part></link><space/>in the<space/><link><target>Sane-et-Loire</target></link><space/><link><target>Departments of France</target><part>department</part></link><space/>of the<space/><link><target>Regions of France</target><part>region</part></link><space/>of<space/><link><target>Burgundy</target></link>, in eastern<space/><link><target>France</target></link>. It is 20&amp;nbsp;km northwest of<space/><link><target>Mcon</target></link>.</paragraph><paragraph>The town grew up around the<space/><link><target>Benedictine</target></link><space/><link><target>Abbey of Cluny</target></link>, founded by Duke<space/><link><target>William I of Aquitaine</target></link><space/>in 910. The height of Cluniac influence was from the second half of the 10th century through the early 12th. The abbey was sacked by the<space/><link><target>Huguenots</target></link><space/>in 1562, and many of its valuable manuscripts were destroyed or removed.</paragraph><heading level='2'>Geography</heading><paragraph>The river<space/><link><target>Grosne River</target><part>Grosne</part></link><space/>flows northward through the commune and crosses the town.</paragraph><heading level='2'>Tourism</heading><paragraph><template><target>Main</target><arg>Tourism in Saône-et-Loire, South Burgundy</arg></template>South Burgundy has a large number of places which are of interest to tourists, such as:</paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem>The<space/><link><target>Arboretum de Pzanin</target></link>, one of the richest arboreta in France</listitem><listitem><link><target>Mcon</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Paray-le-Monial</target></link></listitem><listitem>The<space/><italics>Green Way</italics></listitem></list><heading level='2'>See also</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Cluniac Reforms</target></link></listitem><listitem